07397nam a22010695i 9783110565744DE-B159720230228123812.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230228t20172017gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831105657447 a10.1515/97831105657442doi  a(DE-B1597)487783  a(OCoLC)1004886307  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aLAN0090002bisacsh00aAdvances in Maltese Linguistics /ced. by Benjamin Saade, Mauro Tosco. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter Mouton, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (IX, 274 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudia Typologica [STTYP] : Beihefte / Supplements STUF - Sprachtypologie und Universalienforschung / Language Typology and Universals ,x1617-2957 ;v2100tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tMaltese linguistics: What is new? -- tPart 1: New looks into the past -- tOn the phonology of Sicilian Arabic and early Maltese -- tAspects of the comparison between Maltese, Mediterranean Lingua Franca and the Occitan-Catalan linguistic group (13th–15th centuries) -- tPart 2: Maltese, and just Maltese -- tModifiers and complements within the Maltese verb sequence -- tFocus particles in Maltese: A corpus survey -- tOn prepositional ellipsis and the factors which block its application in Maltese -- tPart 3: Beyond Maltese, now and then -- tVerbal negation with muš in Maltese and Eastern Mediterranean Arabics -- tMaltese kiteb vs. Tunisian (Sūsa) ktib -- tThe phonetic study of speakers along the Maltese-English continuum -- tThe visibility and salience of Maltese in bilingual Malta’s linguistic landscape -- tThe myth of the mixed languages -- tIndex of Authors -- tIndex of Languages -- tIndex of Subjects0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis volume is a collection of up-to-date articles on Maltese on all linguistic levels, demonstrating the variety of topics Maltese has to offer for linguists of all specializations. Two diachronic studies discuss the early contact of Maltese and Sicilian Arabic (Avram) and the possible lexical influence of Occitan-Catalan on Maltese in the 13th-15th century (Biosca & Castellanos).Fabri & Borg shed light on the rules that govern verb sequences in Maltese. Čéplö presents a corpus analysis of the syntactic and semantic properties of focus constructions in Maltese. Stolz & Ahrens analyze the behavior of prepositional phrases with identical heads under coordination. Wilmsen & Al-Sayyed study the use of muš as a negator in Maltese and beyond. Puech presents a detailed phonological analysis of Maltese and Tunisian Arabic based on prosody, syllabic structure, and stress. Azzopardi-Alexander gives a fine-grained analysis of phonological features in Maltese English, placing speakers on a Maltese-English continuum. Sciriha takes a visual approach to multilingualism in Malta with her quantitative study of public and private signs. Finally, Versteegh offers a thought-provoking perspective on the notion "mixed language" and its viability.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aMaltese language. 4aMaltese. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aArabic.  aLanguage Contact.  aMaltese.  aRomance Languages.  aSemitic Languages.1 aAhrens, Carolin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAl-Sayyed, Amany, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAvram, Andrei A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAzzopardi-Alexander, Marie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBiosca, Carles, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBorg, Albert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCastellanos, 